## Reflection
The three agent structure was honestly the best decision right from the beginning.
Seperating MIRA, MIZEL and MILO made everything feel clean, well organized and very structured.
Each agent has their own job that they are responsible for.

MIRA does really well with keyword routing especially for pricing, booking and logistics,
MIZEL also turned out great in terms of giving useful and specific mood directions based on a client's vision.
Adding a passcode to MILO made it feel more realistic and clearly sections between company/business internal usage and clients.

The biggest limitation is that everything is keyword based. So let's say a user phrases something differently than expected,
then the system could miss it and fall back to a generic response. 
To deal with that, I expanded the keyword lists as much as possible by adding synonyms and different ways people could possibly
ask the same thing.

The biggest technical challenge I faced was with MIZEL, translating how someone feels about an event into actual visual direction
is not easy, because it could never be exactly the same as in someone's head.

What helped here was narrowing everything down into few main aestetic categories:
- romantic / blush
- royal / grand
- bold / luxury
- minimalist / modern
- garden / white

If I had more time, I would:
Replace keyword logic with an actual LLM so the system understands any phrasing,
Connect MILO to a real database so inventory can be updated in real time, 
Add booking functionality so clients can schedule directly with MIRA
I actually planned for MIZEL to have a 3D visualizer and image generator but as I was building I realized it was more complex than I thought 
